07730nam a22018015i 9780691238180DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20221993nju    fo  d z      eng d  a9780691238180  a(DE-B1597)609930  a(OCoLC)1291507237  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aPER0040302bisacsh1 aWexman, Virginia Wexman, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCreating the Couple :bLove, Marriage, and Hollywood Performance /cVirginia Wexman Wexman. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©1993  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b189 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tPART I Introduction: The Movies as Social Ritual -- t1. Romantic Love, Changing Marriage Norms, and Stars as Behavioral Models -- tPART II Patriarchal Marriage and Traditional Gender Identities -- t2. Star and Auteur: The Griffith-Gish Collaboration and the Struggle over Patriarchal Marriage -- t3. Star and Genre: John Wayne, the Western, and the American Dream of the Family on the Land -- tPART III Companionate Marriage and Changing Constructions of Gender and Sexuality -- t4. The Love Goddess: Contradictions in the Myth of Glamour -- t5. Masculinity in Crisis: Method Acting in Hollywood -- tPART IV Epilogue: Beyond the Couple -- t6. The Destabilization of Gender Norms and Acting as Performance -- tIllustrations -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWho decides how, when, and where Americans fall in love and get married? Virginia Wexman's acute observations about movie stars and acting techniques show that Hollywood has often had the most powerful voice in demonstrating socially sanctioned ways of becoming a couple. Until now serious film critics have paid little attention to the impact of performance styles on American romance, and have often treated "patriarchy," "sexuality," and the "couple" as monolithic and unproblematic concepts. Wexman, however, shows how these notions have been periodically transformed in close association with the appearance, behavior, and persona of the stars of films such as The Maltese Falcon, The Big Sleep, Way Down East, The Man Who Shot Liberty Valance, Sunset Boulevard, On the Waterfront, Nashville, House of Games, and Do the Right Thing. The author focuses first on the way in which traditional marriage norms relate to authorship (the Griffith-Gish collaboration) and genre (John Wayne and the Western). Looking at male and female stardom in terms of the development of "companionate marriage," she discusses the love goddess and the impact of method acting on Hollywood's ideals of maleness. Finally she considers the recent breakdown of the ideal of monogamous marriage in relation to Hollywood's experimentation with self-reflexive acting styles. Creating the Couple is must reading for film scholars and enthusiasts, and it will fascinate everyone interested in the changing relationships of men and women in modern culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aActing.  aActor.  aAffective memory.  aAnglo.  aBroken Blossoms.  aChapter 1 (House of Cards).  aChapter Two (play).  aCharacter (arts).  aChristian Dior.  aCinema of the United States.  aClassical Hollywood cinema.  aClose-up.  aColonization.  aConsideration.  aCourtship.  aD. W. Griffith.  aDivision of labour.  aDo the Right Thing.  aElia Kazan.  aEndogamy.  aEroticism.  aExogamy.  aFan magazine.  aFemininity.  aFilm noir.  aFilmmaking.  aGary Cooper.  aGender role.  aGenre.  aHegemony.  aHermann Broch.  aHollywood Star.  aHomoeroti